  • Introduction

Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies from 1960 to 2015 collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including various columns about the details of the movies, user ratings and revenue.

  • Certain columns, like ‘cast’ and ‘genres’, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters.
  • There are some odd characters in the ‘cast’ column. Don’t worry about cleaning them. You can leave them as is.
  • The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time

The dataset characteristics has been investigated according to 2 major factors:

  1. Profit
  2. Popularity ### Example Questions
  • What are the characteristics associated with higher profit movies?
  • What are the characteristics associated with most popular movies?
  • Which genre have the highest popularity or the highest profit?
  • Does the vote average affects the movies profit?
  • Which year have the most popular movies?
  • Which year have the higest profit movies movies?

id unique id for each movie.

Popularity a metric used to measure the popularity of the movie.
budget the total budget of the moviein USD.
revenue the total revenue of the movie in USD.
original_title the original title of the movie.
cast the names of the cast of the movie separated by " ".
homepage the website of the movie (if it existed).
director name(s) of the director(s) of the movie.
tagline a catchphrase describing the movie.
keywords keywords related to the movie.
overview summary of the plot of the movie.
runtime total runtime of the movie in minutes.
genres types of the movie separated by " ".
production_companies production compan(y/ies) of the movie.
release_date release date of the movie.
vote_count number of voters of te movie.
vote_average the average user rating of the movie.
release_year release year of the movie (from 1960 to 2015)
budget_adj the total budget of the movie in USD in terms of 2010 dollars.
revenue_adj the total budget of the movie in USD in terms of 2010 dollars.

Looks like the 0 values in budget and revenue are same for budget_adj, revenue_adj respectively.

As we investigating the data in according to the profit, we can't have such zero values in our data.

We can clean them by 2 methods:

  1. Removing them from dataset
  2. Replacing them with the mean of their columns

Removing these rows from the dataset is really bad choice because it will make us lose a huge amount of data which can help in our analysis, also will change the data characteristics as we can see here in "Method 1"

Method 1: removing them from dataset

Method 2: Replacing them with the mean

# Replacing zero values in the datasets
df_re_zero.budget.replace(0, df_re_zero.budget.mean(), inplace = True)
df_re_zero.revenue.replace(0, df_re_zero.revenue.mean(), inplace = True)
df_re_zero.runtime.replace(0, int(df_re_zero.runtime.mean()), inplace = True)
df_re_zero.budget_adj.replace(0, df_re_zero.budget_adj.mean(), inplace = True)
df_re_zero.revenue_adj.replace(0, df_re_zero.revenue_adj.mean(), inplace = True)

In [26]:
# Create new features from the dataset 
df_clean['main_genre']=df_clean.genres.str.split(pat='|',expand=True)[0]
df_clean['hero_actor']=df_clean.cast.str.split(pat='|',expand=True)[0]
df_clean['main_director']=df_clean.director.str.split(pat='|',expand=True)[0]
df_clean['profit'] = df_clean.revenue_adj - df_clean.budget_adj

# Drop unnecessary columns 
df_clean.drop(['genres','cast', 'director', 'budget','revenue'], axis = 1, inplace = True)

That's great. Now, we have our dataset clean and ready to be explored!

With new four columns:

Column Description
main_genre The first genre in the genres list.
hero_actor The first actor in the cast list.
main_director The main director of the movie (if there are more than one director).
profit The net profit of the movie (calculated by profit = revenue_adj - budget_adj).

In [49]:
# Create a function that save for me repetitive code
def bar_plot(df, col_groupby, col_grouped, orient):
    my_variable = df.groupby([col_groupby])[col_grouped].mean()
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(20,20) })
    if orient == 'v':
        sns.barplot(y = my_variable, x = my_variable.index, orient = orient, palette="bright");
    elif orient == 'h':
        sns.barplot(x = my_variable, y = my_variable.index, orient = orient, palette="bright");
    plt.title(str(col_groupby+" Vs "+ col_grouped+ " Average").title(), fontsize = 18, weight = "bold")
In [50]:
# Plotting the mean profit of each main genre 
bar_plot(df_clean,'main_genre', 'profit', 'v')
In [51]:
# Plotting the mean popularity of each main genre 
bar_plot(df_clean,'main_genre', 'popularity', 'v')

It seems that the adventure movies are the most populare movies and have the highest profit. Very interesting!

Conclusions¶

Profit Characterstics¶

  • Higher profit movies has the highest popularity.
  • Steven Spielberg is the director with most movies that made high profit.
  • Renny Harlin is the director with most movies that were lossing.
  • The majority of high profit movies are comedy, drama, action, and Horror respectively.
  • The average runtime of a high profit movie is 107 minutes.
  • Movies with high vote average have higher profit than movies with low vote average.
  • 1977 and 1967 are the years with the most high profit movies respectively.
  • 1966 and 2006 is the year with the least low profit movies respectively

Popularity Characterstics¶

  • Steven Spielberg is the director with most movies are very popular.
  • The majority of high profit movies are drama, comedy, action, and adventure respectively.
  • The adventure movies are the most populare movies and have the highest profit.
  • 2015 and 2014 are the years with the highest average popularity score respectively
  • 1966 is the year with the least average popularity score.

Limitations¶

  • The dataset has many missing values for the budget, revenue and profit.
  • The drama, comedy and action genres are most frequent so they appear in the most popular, least popular and different profit levels of the movies.
  • The charachteristics of the movie does not guarantee the success or the faliure of it.
